{"id":"1707.06877","submitter":"Antonia W. Bluher","authors":"Antonia W. Bluher","title":"Permutation properties of Dickson and Chebyshev polynomials and\n  connections to number theory","comments":"25 pages. First presented as \"Permutations properties of Dickson\n  polynomials and connections to number theory\" at the Mathematical Congress of\n  the Americas, MCA2017. Version of May 1, 2021 is shortened and has a new\n  Theorem 8.1. Submitted to Finite Fields and Their Applications","journal-ref":"Finite Fields and Their Applications 76 (2021)","doi":"10.1016/j.ffa.2021.101899","report-no":null,"categories":"math.NT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The $k$th Dickson polynomial of the first kind, $D_k(x) \\in {\\mathbb Z}[x]$,\nis determined by the formula: $D_k(u+1/u) = u^k + 1/u^k$, where $k \\ge 0$ and\n$u$ is an indeterminate. These polynomials are closely related to Chebyshev\npolynomials and have been widely studied. Leonard Eugene Dickson proved in 1896\nthat $D_k(x)$ is a permutation polynomial on ${\\mathbb F}_{p^n}$, $p$ prime, if\nand only if GCD$(k,p^{2n}-1)=1$, and his result easily carries over to\nChebyshev polynomials when $p$ is odd. This article continues on this theme, as\nwe find special subsets of ${\\mathbb F}_{p^n}$ that are stabilized or permuted\nby Dickson or Chebyshev polynomials. Our analysis also leads to a factorization\nformula for Dickson and Chebyshev polynomials and some new results in\nelementary number theory. For example, we show that if $q$ is an odd prime\npower, then $\\prod\\left\\{ a \\in{\\mathbb F}_q^\\times : \\text{$a$ and $4-a$ are\nnonsquares} \\right\\} = 2$.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 21 Jul 2017 12:50:01 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 31 Jan 2018 01:23:03 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Sat, 1 May 2021 01:00:49 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-08-17"}
